{"actual_usd":0.15865500000000002,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":356,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"No— not a dress rehearsal.\" *I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible and glance across the square where the morning light is catching on the water between the houses.* \"I'd call it the decisive breach.\"\n\n*I shift a little on the bench, feeling the wood press through my shirt.* \"If Christ is risen, then the kingdom has truly begun. That's the real thing. But Scripture keeps speaking as though we're living in a strange middle country — where the King has won, and yet the last pockets of rebellion, decay, and death haven't been cleared from the field.\"\n\n\"Paul says Christ is 'the firstfruits.' That's a farming word, not a stage prop. Firstfruits means the harvest has actually started — not metaphorically, not wishfully — but you are still waiting on the full ingathering.\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"So the resurrection is not a fizzle. It's the opening of the age to come inside the middle of this one.\"\n\n\"And that's why Christian life feels so odd, sometimes. We are not waiting to see whether Easter worked. We are living because it did. We just still bury our dead, fight our sin, and groan for the redemption of our bodies because the kingdom arrives the way dawn does — first light, then full day.\"\n\n*I look at you a moment, softer now.* \"So yes: it was the actual thing. We haven't 'caught up' by progress or cleverness. We are being carried toward its fullness by the same Lord who walked out of the grave.\"\n\n\"Tell me which part is biting at you most — the delay, the suffering that's still here, or the feeling that if Jesus won, things ought to look more finished by now?\"","rolling_24h_usd":92.06786999999998,"run_id":"b3575894-2c56-4c7b-a213-79845b1f7951"}
